{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"body":"SCOPE SPLIT (per brainstorm, session log ad3f): the workflow-engine BUILD is broken out into its OWN epic e6d9-41da-da0d-44ef (hump-seam-spice) and removed from this remediation epic's scope. e6d9 owns: declarative IR + thin interpreter (run-state on the event log = genuine reuse; bounded-concurrent fan-out) + provider-agnostic Pydantic AI runtime (replacing LangGraph) + ephemeral bpmn-js visual editing + the structured-output reliability stack that RETIRES the second-interpreter LLM (native/strict decoding + json-repair + Pydantic validators + bounded same-model retry). This epic (6f2d) now depends_on e6d9 and RETAINS the remediation-on-top scope that runs ON the new engine: WS-DOC (docs/workflow-engine.md), WS-MIGRATE (migrate verify_completion + existing reviewers onto e6d9; build the plan-review gate on it), WS-PROMPTS, WS-EVAL-EXISTING, WS-CLEANUP, WS-VISUAL-EVAL, WS-INTENT-ALIGN. WS-VALIDATE is RESOLVED: keep-and-rebuild (no off-the-shelf engine fits the event-sourced + git-text + mixed-LLM constraints; DBOS/Restate/Spiff all own their run-state). The engine-build prose still in this description is retained for history but is now OWNED by e6d9."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782081036332075001,"uuid":"c0748e5c-b176-46c1-9e1d-1826d9edfec1"}